Exercise 2: Linear regression

(a)

the build of a predictive model for the lcavol variable

model <- lm(formula = lcavol ~ . , data = prostateCancer )

considering gleason and svi as qualitative variables

prostateCancer$gleason<-factor(prostateCancer$gleason)
prostateCancer$svi<-factor(prostateCancer$svi)

the mathematical equation of the regression model :

lcavol = \(\beta_0\) + \(\beta_1\) lpsa + \(\beta_2\) lweight + \(\beta_3\) age + \(\beta_4\) lbph + \(\beta_5\) svi + \(\beta_6\) lcp + \(\beta_7\) gleason + \(\beta_8\) pgg45 + \(\epsilon\)

where \(\beta_i\) is intrepreted as te average effect on lcavol of an unit increase in of the variable thar corresponds to \(\beta_i\) while holding all other predictors fixed and \(\epsilon\) is the noise variable that has zero mean, constant variance, and is uncorrolated with lcavol

The optimality of the model

First the value if the sum_squares if not that big but to see how much our model is optimal we will compare to some basic models

the first model tha we will use predict always the same number which is the average of lcavol obtained from the data

the second model predict each time a random value from the intervalle that begins from the min value of lcavol and max value of lcavol

First model :

moyenne_lcavol <- mean(lcavol)

predict_always_average <- c(1:length(lcavol))
for (i in 1:length(lcavol)){
  predict_always_average[i] <- moyenne_lcavol
}
diff2 <- predict_always_average  - lcavol
sum_sq <- sum(diff2**2)
sum_sq

Second model :

data_alea <- runif(97, min = min(lcavol), max = max(lcavol))

the sum of squares of both these models is much bigger so we can say that our model is good

(b).

list_cb <- combn(8, 2)
rss <- c()
best_estm <- Inf

for(e in seq(1, 28)) {
  model_i <- lm(lcavol~., data = prostateCancer[, c(1, list_cb[, c(e)][1] + 1, list_cb[, c(e)][2] + 1)])
  rss_i <- sum(model_i$residuals^2)
  rss <- c(rss, rss_i)
  if(best_estm > rss_i){
    best_estm <- rss_i
    best_set <- list_cb[, c(e)]
  }
}
dimnames(prostateCancer[, c(best_set + c(1, 1))])

(c).

rss <- c()
m_use <- matrix(0, nrow = 9, ncol = 9)

for(k in seq(0, 8)){
  list_cb <- combn(8, k)
  best_estm <- Inf
  n <- choose(8, k)
  best_set <- c(1)
  
  if(k>0){
    for(e in seq(1, n)) {
      pred_list <- c(1)
      if(k > 0){
        for(i in seq(1, k)){
          pred_list <- c(pred_list, list_cb[, c(e)][i])
        }
      }
      
      model_i <- lm(lcavol~., data = prostateCancer[, c(1, pred_list + 1)])
      rss_i <- sum(model_i$residuals^2)
      if(best_estm > rss_i){
        best_estm <- rss_i
        best_set <- list_cb[, c(e)]
      }
    }
    rss <- c(rss, rss_i)
    best_set <- best_set + 1
  }
  
  for(i in seq(0,k)){
    m_use[k+1 , best_set[i]] <- 1
  }
  if(k>0){
    print(best_set)
  }
}

(d).

Minimizing the RSS results in choosing the maximum size of predictors which is accurate since receiving the maximum of information provided is the naive way to predict the variable. However, it does not give a well suited criteria to pick the optimal size of regression model. The RSS decreases as we add more variables to the model whether they are relevant or not which does not serve our quest in predicting the variable since it may not improve the model’s predective power or generalizability.

Selecting an optimal size of the regression model should balance between its complexity and its ability to fit the data and make accurate predictions. We may be able to achieve this by using model selection technique of Akaike Information Criterion AIC.

Exercice 4:

(a).

In split validation we split the data to training and validation sets and we evaluate the model on validation data that was not used during the training. This allows us to avoid overfitting which occurs when we tweak the model to fit perfectly our data, but on unseen data the prediction are not necessarily accurate.

(b).

#Choosing the validation set
valid <- seq(from = 3, to = nrow(prostateCancer), by = 3 )

(c).

The use of lm(lcavol∼ . ,data=prostateCancer[!valid, c(1, i, j)]) creates a regression model using only data that won’t be used in the validation, which is the training data

trained <- lm(lcavol~., data=prostateCancer[-valid, c(1, 6, 9)])
predictions_training <- predict(trained)
mean_training_error <- mean((prostateCancer[-valid, ]$lcavol - predictions_training)^2)
#Calculating the mean training error
mean_training_error
## [1] 0.4616663

(d).

#We predict the results for data not used in the training
predictions_validation <- predict(trained, prostateCancer[valid, ])
mean_validation_error <- mean((prostateCancer[valid, ]$lcavol - predictions_validation)^2)
mean_validation_error
## [1] 0.5672302

(e).

validation_errors <- c()
training_errors <- c()
for (k in c(2:9)){
  trained_k <- lm(prostateCancer[-valid,]$lcavol~., data=prostateCancer[-valid, c(1, which(m_use[k,] == 1))])
  
  predictions_validation_k <- predict(trained_k, prostateCancer[valid, ])
  predictions_train_k <- predict(trained_k)
  
  
  mean_validation_error_k <- mean((prostateCancer[valid, ]$lcavol - predictions_validation_k)^2)
  mean_train_error_k <- mean((prostateCancer[-valid, ]$lcavol - predictions_train_k)^2)
  training_errors <- c(training_errors, mean_train_error_k)
  validation_errors  <- c(validation_errors, mean_validation_error_k)
}

plot(seq(1:8), training_errors, type = "l", col = "red", xlab = "model size", ylab = "error", ylim = c(0.4, 0.9))
lines(seq(1:8), validation_errors, col = "green")
legend("topright", legend = c("training error", "validation error"), col = c("red", "green"), lty = 1)

We can see that the training error remains low. That’s because the more predictors we use the more we fit our data, however this is cannot be used to conclude the optimal model size. Thus we use the validation error to select the best model size and it appears to be the model with 5 predictors.

(f).

The main problem that could occur is the fact that the choice of the training set is random and it could end up in a set that doesn’t provide good training for the model To address this problem we can use cross validation technique

# Size of dataset
#We use 80% percent of the data for cross validation and we keep the last 20% percent for testing
N_cv = nrow(prostateCancer)
K <- 5
#loop through the sizes of the model
cvError_size <- vector (mode="numeric", length=8)
for (p in 2:9){
  cvError_k <- vector (mode="numeric", length=K)
  #loop through the folds 
  for (k in 1:K){
    # choose the indices of the samples for the fold k-th
    id_val <- k + seq(0, N_cv-K, by=K)
    id_val <- setdiff(id_val, 37)
    # get the training dataset
    f <- lm(prostateCancer[-id_val, ]$lcavol~., data=prostateCancer[-id_val, c(1, which(m_use[p,] == 1))])
    # get the prediction error to estimate data from validation set
    data_to_predict = prostateCancer[id_val, c(1, which(m_use[p,] == 1))] 
    error <- predict(f, data_to_predict) - prostateCancer[id_val, ]$lcavol
    # calculate the mean squared error for this fold
    cvError_k[k] <- mean(error^2)
  }
  cvError_size[p]  <- mean(cvError_k)
}
optimal_size <- which.min(cvError_size[-1])
#Optimal size model
optimal_size
## [1] 5

The result for the best model size is 5 which is similar to the split-validation results. But the two methods could differ with the data

Exercise 5 : Conclusion

We conclude thus that the best model is the one with 5 predictors :age, lcp, gleason, pgg45, lpsa.

To apply the model, we split into training and validations sets and the quality can be deduced from the validation error.
